# Lazy Loading Standards

## Pattern

This codebase uses **`React.lazy`** and **`Suspense`** directly (there is **no** central **`renderLazy`** utility).

- Use **`lazy(async () => import("…"))`** with **statically analyzable** import paths under **`src/`** (same **`baseUrl`** rules as normal imports).
- Wrap lazy content in **`<Suspense fallback={…}>`** with a sensible fallback (loading UI, **`null`**, or an existing skeleton component — avoid raw unstyled loading text in user-facing areas).

## Examples in this repo

- [src/pages/PriceDetailsPage/PriceDetailsPageContent/PriceDetailsPageContent.tsx](mdc:src/pages/PriceDetailsPage/PriceDetailsPageContent/PriceDetailsPageContent.tsx) — lazy sub-features under **`shared/PriceDetails/`**
- [src/pages/LeadPage/LeadPageMobile/LeadPageMobile.tsx](mdc:src/pages/LeadPage/LeadPageMobile/LeadPageMobile.tsx) — lazy sections (e.g. **`DeactivateLead`**, **`ChatbotTileSection`**)

## Guidelines

1. **Fallback:** Match design system / existing skeletons; keep i18n in mind (no hardcoded English loading strings in product UI unless already the pattern nearby).
2. **Boundaries:** Lazy-load at **route** or **heavy section** level; avoid tiny lazy splits that harm readability.
3. **Testing:** **`npm test`** / Storybook — lazy boundaries may need **`Suspense`** wrappers in tests; see **testing-standards.mdc**.

